  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 소순(蔬筍)의 냄새 : '
    value: 승려의 시문이나 언사에 나타나는 말투나 특징을 비꼬아 이르는 말.
english:
  title: A Farewell Message to Wolchang
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    While Mokeun was taking refuge from the heat at Sinreuk Temple by the Yeoggang River, I encountered a certain monk—tall in stature, dark of face. At first sight, I found him peculiar. I spoke to him, but he did not reply. Puzzled, I asked a nearby monk about him. "He is one who keeps silent," came the answer. My confusion dissolved. I thought to myself that such a man is rare in this world, and I felt considerable respect for him.

    Thereafter, when he began to speak, his words carried no trace of monastic affectation. I inquired about his origins. It turned out he had once been skilled in music and accomplished in painting. With wine, he drank like a whale drawing in a river. At chess, he played like wildfire consuming fields. With the spear, even the ancient generals of old could not match him. As for what he conceals and does not speak of—well, there is no need to ask about such things.

    Yet suddenly he cast all this aside. Facing the wall, he sits unmoved. His body does not stir, his words do not leave his lips. Heaven's way has shifted once more, perhaps twice. One can perceive the vastness of his spirit, the steadfastness of his heart. If he continues thus, he shall accomplish great deeds.

    Now, it seems he ventures beyond the capital to seek alms and support—a wish for blessings above and benefit below. His aspirations are indeed grand.

    Tall frame, spirited bearing, steadfast heart, vast ambition—these are qualities rarely possessed by men, and few embody them all together. Yet my only concern is whether Wolchang will nurture and preserve these gifts. Wolchang, I urge you: be vigilant. As the sage Zou once said, "The Way cannot be pursued without care." If you truly maintain the excellence of your nature and preserve the rightness of the path, then that spiritual power and wondrous function will never stray from this foundation.
  footnotes:
    - Wolchang (月牕) was the Buddhist name of the monk being addressed in this farewell.
    - The "monastic affectation" refers to an artificial, pretentious manner of speech characteristic of certain monks.
    - The reference to Zou (鄒國) alludes to the Confucian sage tradition of cautious cultivation of virtue.
